{
  "answer": "The poem is **Insaan** (Chapter 14) from Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*.[^1]\n\nIt portrays humanity as an \"Enigma apart, / And hide that Enigma from his own gaze,\" contrasting this with self-knowing elements of nature: rivers surging to the ocean, winds bearing clouds, stars reveling in their fated orbits, and the sun that \"hides behind the western mountain’s crest, / And drinks the cup of twilight, and finds rest.\"[^2][^3]\n\nThe closing couplet laments:  \n\"There is no one to share the sorrow of Man;  \nHow bitter is the existence of Man!\"[^4]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Chapter 14: Insaan](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Chapter 14: Insaan](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation/#p-d7ec8e).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Chapter 14: Insaan](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation/#p-edc3e3).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Chapter 14: Insaan](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation/#p-62d764).",
